Why America's President Bush Must Not Be Re-elected
I have never been particularly politically engaged, but these are no ordinary times.
President George W. Bush endangers the security of the United States and the world and simultaneously undermines American values.
Due to my opposition to him, I was cursed by Bush's campaign team.
President Bush ran in 2000 with a campaign program promising a policy of "humility" in foreign affairs.
If he is re-elected, this will be a vote for the Bush doctrine of preventive war - and the invasion of Iraq -, and the world will have to live with the consequences.
By rejecting Bush's policy at the ballot box, America has a chance to regain the respect and support of the world.
The terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001 required a strong response.
They have also led to the suspension of the critical process so essential to democracy - the comprehensive and honest discussion of the pending issues.
Bush silenced criticism by labeling it unpatriotic.
For 18 months following September 11th, he managed to suppress any dissent.
In this way, he led America in the wrong direction.
Indeed, Bush played Osama bin Laden directly into his hands.
The invasion of Afghanistan - where bin Laden lived and Al Qaeda maintained their training camps - was justified.
The invasion of Iraq was not.
It was an unintended gift from Bush to bin Laden.
Immediately following September 11th, spontaneous expressions of sympathy for America occurred all over the world.
These have given way to widespread bitterness.
Clearly more people than on September 11th are today willing to risk their lives to kill Americans.
Bush often claims that terrorists hate Americans for who they are - a freedom-loving people - and not for what they do.
War and occupation, however, produce innocent victims.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers - more than 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world also counts the Iraqis killed every day - perhaps twenty times as many.
Just as little was the torture of detainees at the Abu Ghraib prison the work of a few "bad apples".
It was part of a system for dealing with prisoners set up by Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld.
The world public condemns America, and our troops in Iraq pay the price for it.
Bush convinced the people that America's security is in good hands by addressing the fears caused by the September 11 attacks.
In times of danger, people gather around their flag, and Bush exploited this by fostering a sense of threat.
His campaign is based on the assumption that people ultimately do not care about the truth and will almost believe anything if it is repeated often enough.
Something must be wrong with America when we fall for it.
For example, about 40% of all Americans still believe that Saddam Hussein was involved in 9/11, although the 9/11 Commission - appointed by Bush and chaired by a Republican - clearly concluded that no such connection existed.
One would like to scream: "Wake up, America.
Don't you realize that we are being led by the nose?"
The war in Iraq was based on false assumptions from the beginning to the end - if it indeed came to an end.
It was a war of choice, not of necessity.
Much more, America entered the war under a pretext: mass destruction weapons could not be found, and the connection to Al Qaeda cannot be proven.
Bush then claimed that America went to war to liberate Iraq.
But one cannot impose democracy by force on anyone.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqis - and the world - can be glad that they are rid of him.
America, however, had the duty to ensure justice and order; instead, we stood idly by as Baghdad and other cities were looted.
If it had really been about the Iraqi people, we would have had to deploy a larger number of soldiers for the occupation.
We would have had to protect not only the Ministry of Oil, but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Worse still: Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they used methods - such as breaking into private homes and mistreating prisoners - that pushed the population around and humiliated them, thereby causing bitterness and anger.
The retreats and missteps of the Bush administration are numerous.
First, the Iraqi army was dissolved, then America tried to reestablish it.
First, the US tried to eliminate the Baathists, then America sought their help.
When the uprisings could no longer be controlled, America installed an Iraqi government.
The man chosen as their leader was a CIA protégé with a reputation as a "strong man" - an anything but democratic decision.
Despite the efforts of Bush's campaign team to spin the situation positively, the situation in Iraq remains bleak.
A large part of the western territory was left to the insurgents. The prospects for holding free and fair elections in January are rapidly diminishing.
Civil war threatens.
Bush's war in Iraq has also caused immense damage to America, weakened its military power, and undermined the morale of the troops.
Before the war, America could project an image of overwhelming strength.
Not anymore.
Afghanistan is slipping from control.
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan and other countries are once again pursuing nuclear programs with renewed energy.
One can criticize the Bush administration on many other political issues, but none of them is as significant as Iraq.
The cost of the war so far amounts to nearly 200 billion dollars and will continue to rise, because the invasion of Iraq was much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush taunted John Kerry, asking him to explain what he would do differently.
Kerry replied that he would have done everything differently and that he would be in a better position to free us from our entanglements.
Aber auch ihm wird dies nicht leicht fallen, denn Amerika steckt in einem Sumpf.
Führende Militärexperten und Diplomaten haben Bush händeringend gewarnt, nicht in den Irak einzumarschieren.
Er hat sie ignoriert.
Er hat den kritischen Prozess unterdrückt, mit dem Argument, dass jede Kritik am Oberbefehlshaber die US-Truppen gefährde.
Aber dies ist Bushs Krieg, und er sollte dafür zur Verantwortung gezogen werden.
The Americans should pause for a moment and ask themselves: To whom do we owe this mess?
A moment of reflection might raise another question: Is Bush's cowboy demeanor qualified to keep him as America's top commander?
